<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-16T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-16T03:00:00-05:00" n="374" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d374">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1436: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Nanking (<persName type="from">Peck</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-16T16:00:00+08:00">February 16, 1932—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 16—7:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>52. In view of the probability that disturbance Shanghai-Nanking Railway
                            zone as a result of the present hostilities at Shanghai I have again
                            today advised that American women and children and such men as can be
                            spared evacuate from Chinkiang and Chaotou [?]. Shanghai has already
                            advised all Americans at Soochow and Wusih to evacuate. United States
                            ship <hi rend="italic">Bulmer</hi> is at Chinkiang to assist Americans
                            evacuating from or through that port.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>